Example 1: Normal Function
def greet():
    print("Good Morning")

greet()

Output:

Good Morning
Example 2: Infinite Recursion
def greet():
    print("Hello Sir")
    greet()

greet()

In this example, greet() keeps calling itself forever because there is no stopping condition.

What Happens in Infinite Recursion?

Every time a function is called, Python stores it in the call stack.

greet()
greet()
greet()
greet()
greet()
...

As more function calls are added, the stack keeps growing.

Eventually, the stack becomes full, which causes an error.

Stack Overflow

When recursion never stops, the call stack becomes full.

This situation is called Stack Overflow.

Python raises an error instead of running forever.

Python Recursion Limit

Python allows only a limited number of recursive function calls.

Default recursion limit is around 1000 calls (commonly about 1000).
If this limit is exceeded, Python raises:
RecursionError: maximum recursion depth exceeded
How to Avoid Infinite Recursion?

Always provide a Base Case (Stopping Condition).

A base case tells the function when to stop calling itself.

Example
def greet(n):
    if n == 0:      # Base Case
        return

    print("Hello")
    greet(n - 1)

greet(5)

Output

Hello
Hello
Hello
Hello
Hello
Key Points
Recursion means a function calls itself.
Every recursive call is stored in the call stack.
Without a base case, recursion becomes infinite.
Infinite recursion causes a Stack Overflow.
Python stops it by raising a RecursionError after reaching the maximum recursion depth.
Always include a base case to terminate recursion.
